    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_821413836" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/821413836" />
    <a title="Faisal Pakkali" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27614962-faisal-pakkali"><img alt="Faisal Pakkali" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1389556363p2/27614962.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/821413836?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Faisal Pakkali" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Faisal Pakkali" href="/user/show/27614962-faisal-pakkali">Faisal Pakkali</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer821413836" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5863069778761903347">After reading the first short story in Junot Diaz’s collection “Drown’, I went on to the internet to browse for reviews. To be frank, I didn’t understand any of them. The reviews talk about issues of identity in the context of the immigrant experience and all that jazz. However the story still stuck with me despite my lack of knowledge of the Dominican Republic and the urban communities of New Jersey.<br/><br/>The story is basically about two brothers, Rafa and Yunior who become fascinated by a boy named </span>
  <span id="freeText5863069778761903347" style="display:none">After reading the first short story in Junot Diaz’s collection “Drown’, I went on to the internet to browse for reviews. To be frank, I didn’t understand any of them. The reviews talk about issues of identity in the context of the immigrant experience and all that jazz. However the story still stuck with me despite my lack of knowledge of the Dominican Republic and the urban communities of New Jersey.<br /><br />The story is basically about two brothers, Rafa and Yunior who become fascinated by a boy named Ysrael. The boy had been attacked by a pig when he was a child, his face brutally mangled. He is notorious for his grotesque appearance throughout the area and hides his face with a mask. Children often attack and insult him, both frightened and scornful of him. Rafa and Yunior go on a trip to meet Ysrael and possibly see his face. A violent episode ensues.<br /><br />The most immediate reason for my attraction towards this story is the prose. Rich and poetic yet spare and straightforward, the Spanish words that lace the prose, only adds to it an exotic quality. The second reason would be that I, as a reader, share the main character’s fascination with poor Ysrael’s involuntary promise of the grotesque. However the story is not simply a catchy tale told in beautiful prose. It seems rich with meaning under the surface of it’s simple narrative.<br /><br />The story is divided into six small parts and details the lives of the boys in the countryside (campo) and also introduces and elaborates on the character of Ysrael. The crux of the story is the two boys’ quest to find out what is under his mask.<br /><br />Funnily enough, the only truly sympathetic character is Ysrael. Rafa is shown to be somewhat violent and unscrupulous, while Yunior is cowardly. When they meet him, Ysrael is shown to be an outcast not only because of his face and because of his huge size, but even in his dressing. He is dressed completely in “North-American” clothes that his father sends him regularly. Rafa has only one set of these that he wears every time he goes to meet girls.<br /><br />The most important issue here is of course the mask. It’s purpose is to hide something terrible, but in itself becomes a symbol, a herald of this terrible thing. So the mask is a failure. It betrays Ysrael by attracting as much attention as his face would. It teases the onlookers, tantalizing them into wondering what is under the mask. It may even make him seem more monstrous than he really is. The moment when his face is described in the story and given fixed definition is actually quite anticlimactic to the reader, even though it admittedly, scares Yunior.<br /><br />I found myself wondering this while reading the story: Would the world end if Ysrael walked out with his bare face for everyone to see?<br /><br />Maybe I am being naive. Maybe the world would end for Ysrael. But the mask that he wears seems more trouble than it’s worth. And maybe that’s what the story could be about. The consequences of Ysrael hiding who he really is versus the shame and ostracism associated with his identity.<br /><br />And there is more to it actually. At the closing of the story Rafa and Yunior have a conversation about Ysrael’s face. Yunior holds out hope that things will get better for Ysrael and that medical help would be able to do something for him. Yunior shows more sympathy towards Ysrael than Rafa. Perhaps the timid Yunior felt a kinship towards the outcast Ysrael. And perhaps he, like Ysrael, hopes or a better future. However Rafa issues a warning to him. There is no point in running away from who you really are.<br /><br />*<br /><br />Ysrael will be Ok, I said.<br /><br />Don’t bet on it.<br /><br />They’re going to fix him.<br /><br />A muscle fluttered between his jaw bone and his ear. Yunior, he said tiredly. They aren’t going to do shit to him.<br /><br />How do you know?<br /><br />I know, he said.<br /><br />*</span>
  <a data-text-id="5863069778761903347" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


